To provision an Amazon S3 bucket with a bucket-level CORS configuration in Terraform, we need to define two primary resources: `aws_s3_bucket` for the storage and `aws_s3_bucket_cors_configuration` for the cross-origin rules. 

In the CORS configuration, the mandatory fields are `allowed_methods` (HTTP verbs like GET or POST) and `allowed_origins` (the domains permitted to access the bucket). We will also include `allowed_headers` and `max_age_seconds` to provide a complete, functional example.

```hcl
# Configure the AWS Provider
provider "aws" {
  region = "us-east-1"
}

# 1. Provision the S3 Bucket
resource "aws_s3_bucket" "example_bucket" {
  bucket = "terraform-ai-sample-cors-bucket-${random_id.id.hex}"

  tags = {
    Name        = "My Terraform Bucket"
    Environment = "Dev"
  }
}

# Generate a random ID to ensure bucket name uniqueness
resource "random_id" "id" {
  byte_length = 4
}

# 2. Define the CORS configuration resource for the bucket
# Note: In AWS Provider v4+, CORS is managed as a standalone resource
resource "aws_s3_bucket_cors_configuration" "example_cors" {
  bucket = aws_s3_bucket.example_bucket.id

  cors_rule {
    # Mandatory: Specifies which headers are allowed in a pre-flight request
    allowed_headers = ["*"]

    # Mandatory: Specifies which HTTP methods are allowed
    allowed_methods = ["PUT", "POST", "GET", "DELETE"]

    # Mandatory: Specifies which origins can access the bucket
    allowed_origins = ["https://s3-website-test.hashicorp.com", "http://localhost:3000"]

    # Optional: Specifies which headers are exposed to the browser
    expose_headers  = ["ETag"]

    # Optional: Specifies how long the browser should cache the pre-flight response (in seconds)
    max_age_seconds = 3000
  }
}

